              Those numbers are about signs. But the same principle applies to murals, and the gap between hand-painted and vinyl is even wider at mural scale.
            </p>
            <p
              class="font-body text-soft-gray"
              style="font-size: var(--text-fluid-lg); line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);"
            >
              A vinyl mural is a printed image applied in strips, like wallpaper. It was designed on a screen, printed on a machine, and mailed in a tube. It could have been installed on any wall in any city. It belongs nowhere because it could have been anywhere. People process it the way they process advertising: they see it, they register it, they move on.
            </p>
            <p
              class="font-body text-soft-gray"
              style="font-size: var(--text-fluid-lg); line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);"
            >
              A hand-painted mural is made in the presence of the wall. The colors are mixed for that specific surface. The lines carry the hand of the person who painted them. People register this difference instinctively. The slight variations in the brushwork, the density and warmth of real pigment, the way paint sits differently than ink on plastic. A hand-painted mural becomes a destination. A vinyl wrap becomes background.
            </p>
            <p
              class="font-body text-soft-gray"
              style="font-size: var(--text-fluid-lg); line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);"
            >
              The visual science backs this up. Alkyd enamel achieves a 90+ Gardner gloss reading, creating what painters call optical depth: the perception of color glowing from within the surface rather than sitting flat on top of it (Ronan enamel technical documentation). Digital printing lays ink on a plastic film. The result is flatter, thinner, and shallower. People notice even when they can&rsquo;t name why.
            </p>
            <p
              class="font-body text-soft-gray"
              style="font-size: var(--text-fluid-lg); line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);"
