            >
              <strong class="text-titanium-white">Temporary signage.</strong> Event banners, seasonal promotions, grand opening signs you plan to remove within a year. Vinyl is fast, cheap, and disposable. That is exactly what temporary signage should be.
            </p>
            <p
              class="font-body text-soft-gray"
              style="font-size: var(--text-fluid-lg); line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);"
            >
              <strong class="text-titanium-white">Interior applications.</strong> Vinyl on interior walls and windows lasts much longer without UV exposure and temperature cycling. Window lettering for hours, menus, or directional signage is a legitimate use.
            </p>
            <p
              class="font-body text-soft-gray"
              style="font-size: var(--text-fluid-lg); line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);"
            >
              <strong class="text-titanium-white">Short-term locations.</strong> If you&rsquo;re in a space for two to three years and plan to move, vinyl makes financial sense. You won&rsquo;t be there long enough for the hand-painted sign to pay for itself.
            </p>
            <p
              class="font-body text-soft-gray"
              style="font-size: var(--text-fluid-lg); line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);"
            >
              <strong class="text-titanium-white">Where vinyl is the wrong choice:</strong> permanent storefronts, exterior brick or wood, buildings in historic districts, any location where the sign needs to last more than three years, and anywhere the sign faces direct sun. In those situations, vinyl costs more over time, looks worse over time, and can damage the surface underneath.
            </p>
            <p
              class="font-body text-soft-gray"
              style="font-size: var(--text-fluid-lg); line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);"
